    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4362769837" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4362769837" />
    <a title="JimZ" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/99765491-jimz"><img alt="JimZ" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1575257175p2/99765491.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4362769837?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="JimZ" class="user" itemprop="url" name="JimZ" href="/user/show/99765491-jimz">JimZ</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4362769837" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7805959559031423139">I made the mistake of seeking out a synopsis of this novel early on in the reading because I didn’t know who one of the characters was ….I was getting confused as to who Judy Trenor was versus Bertha Dorset, so anyhoo I looked up who-was-who, and got my answer, but after I got my answer and I was still on Google there were a whole bunch of other questions that Google could supply the answers to just by a click of the computer mouse….and there was the question “Why does Bertha Dorset hate Lily Ba</span>
  <span id="freeText7805959559031423139" style="display:none">I made the mistake of seeking out a synopsis of this novel early on in the reading because I didn’t know who one of the characters was ….I was getting confused as to who Judy Trenor was versus Bertha Dorset, so anyhoo I looked up who-was-who, and got my answer, but after I got my answer and I was still on Google there were a whole bunch of other questions that Google could supply the answers to just by a click of the computer mouse….and there was the question “Why does Bertha Dorset hate Lily Bart?” and like the damn fool that I am I had to click on the question to get the answer which was <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ ‘A woman universally known for her manipulation and cruelty, Bertha Dorset feels threatened by Lily Bart and experiences no remorse at taking revenge on her, ultimately condemning her to poverty and social exclusion.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> Why did I have to click on that question??? What was I expecting? Something other than a direct answer which would have somehow satisfied me yet maintained my ignorance as to why Betha hated Lily even though that was a key element of the book that Edith Wharton in due time would tell me if I was just patient enough!!! But no…I had to go to a modern-day version of Cliff Notes. I had to know the answer with still over 250 pages to go in the damn book. So, I already know how the book is going to end regarding the main character…fer chrissake!!! What was I thinking??? 🙁<br /><br />So, while reading this I had this cloud of doom and gloom over my head. 🙁<br /><br />Lily Bart reminded me of Scarlett O’Hara in ‘Gone with the Wind’. There was perhaps an ounce of good in Scarlett’s bones but that was about it. She was a selfish conniving person. And it seemed that Lily was that way too throughout most of the book, but so were pretty much everybody else in the novel. I suppose Lawrence Selden was different from the rich folks in the novel. He was likable and so was his cousin Gerty Farish. But that’s where the goodness ended and the lazy people who inherited their wealth and reveled in gawdy conspicuous wealth began. Ugh. <br /><br />Although I did feel sorry for Lily near the end of the novel. <br /><br />Even though I knew pretty much how it was going to end, Edith Wharton’s telling of the story still held my interest. I think I will read “The Custom of the Country” but I will try my best to remain ignorant of the plot or its denouement so please don’t anybody tell me about how that book ends. Thank you kindly. 🙃 😉<br /><br />Reviews<br />•	by Jennifer Egan, very fine review…but do not read it (yet) if you want to read the book and not have its ending spoiled..,. <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/jan/11/the-house-of-mirth-jennifer-egan-on-edith-whartons-masterpiece">https://www.theguardian.com/books/202...</a> <br />•	a review of the book when it was first published in 1905… <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://bookmarks.reviews/a-103-year-old-review-of-edith-whartons-the-house-of-mirth/">https://bookmarks.reviews/a-103-year-...</a> <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7805959559031423139" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


